{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a2bd4c1c-64e7-4e19-b32c-e94777d6f7f6","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, so I'll give you the configuration guidance directly.\n\nTo publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org, add these properties to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- Required NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/repo</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n\n  <!-- Recommended for stdio MCP servers -->\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <RollForward>Major</RollForward>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n| Property | Purpose |\n|----------|---------|\n| `PackAsTool` | Marks the project as a dotnet tool |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users invoke (e.g., `my-mcp-server`) |\n| `OutputType=Exe` | Required — tools must be executables |\n| `RollForward=Major` | Lets users run on newer .NET versions |\n\n**Publishing steps:**\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_KEY --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n**Users install with:**\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\n```\n\nThen configure their MCP client to run `my-mcp-server` via stdio.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2d811c92-542b-4fc2-88bf-d51016fce4f4","outputTokens":482,"requestId":"2C06:9A895:2A1B772:2E7BEDD:69FD36CF"},"id":"29134776-ce42-4bf6-8369-edc567430a77","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:05:28.729Z","parentId":"ca05f794-5288-400c-85b9-0256b0cebc11"}
